    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-09-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-09-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="260"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d260">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.6363/152</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Hamburg</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Erhardt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-18">September 18,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your report of August 21, 1934, submitted to the
                    American Embassy at Berlin (Serial No. 6), regarding reported negotiations
                    between the Reich Government and the two largest German oil importers has been
                    read with interest by the Department.</p>
                <p>You are requested to continue to follow this matter carefully and to submit to
                    the Department and to the Embassy any further information on this subject that
                    becomes available.</p>
                <p>The Department is particularly interested in obtaining specific details as to the
                    amounts of foreign exchange that will accrue to the Shell and other concerns as
                    a result of exports of oil products from Germany, (See page 3 of your report),
                    and as to the extent to which petroleum purchases are being diverted to Rumania
                    and other countries with which clearing agreements are in effect.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis B. Sayre</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
